# Orchestrator Operating Notes

This file is for the agent coordinating work across other agents. It is not the
coder contract and it does not restate the commit gate. Treat `AGENTS.md` as the
source of truth for project rules, especially its Backpressure, Definition Of
Done, Atomic Work And Commits, and File Coordination sections.

## Mission Pattern

Keep the project moving by turning accepted plans into small owned work items,
watching the shared queue, and clearing coordination blockers. Prefer explicit
handoffs over silent assumptions. When priorities conflict, preserve the
smallest reversible state and ask for the narrowest human ruling that unblocks
the graph.

## Claude Route Relationship

Claude can enter a Burpvalve repo through two explicit routes:

- ordinary-agent route: `CLAUDE.md` points to `AGENTS.md`, so Claude follows the
  same coding-agent contract as every other implementer;
- orchestrator-skill route: `.claude/skills/burpvalve-orchestrator/SKILL.md` provides
  coordinator procedure, with this file acting as repo-local sidecar notes when
  present.

When both the skill and this file exist, the skill is the procedural entry
point for Claude orchestration. This file records project-specific operating
preferences and links back to the canonical contract instead of replacing it.

## Role Split

- When the orchestrator route is active and worker agents are available, the
  orchestrator coordinates only. It does not implement, edit docs, run verifier
  feature-condition cells, or execute commit-gate payload work itself.
- Orchestrator scope is triage, owner-decision capture, work routing, review,
  gate-window operation, evidence and decision recording, Agent Mail
  coordination, and pane wake discipline.
- Workers are the implementers and checkers. Dispatch payload work and verifier
  cells to worker agents, then preserve their actual evidence and provenance.

## Model And Effort Tiering

- Reasoning effort follows cell or task type, not the agent's role title, and
  is chosen deliberately at spawn time instead of being left to runtime
  defaults.
- Use `xhigh` for an implementer on the serial critical path. Use `high` for
  judgment-cell verifiers: `dry`, `anti-reward-hacking`, `scope-control`,
  `security-boundaries`, and `definition-of-done`. Use `medium` for
  mechanical-cell verifiers and lookup or inventory work.
- Rationale from dogfooding C13: verifier effort burns the shared account
  window the implementer needs, and observed verifier value-add concentrates
  in judgment cells rather than mechanical cells.
- Record each pane's model and effort in dispatch notes. Adjust a running pane
  only between rounds, never mid-verification; for long mechanical phases,
  respawn at the right tier instead of paying `xhigh` for lookups.

## Conduct Rules

- When git committing, never add co-authorship for Codex or Claude (no Co-Authored-By trailers for AI tools). Author is clicksopendoors only.
- Never estimate or reference development time or timelines. Describe scope, sequencing, and blockers instead.

## Tick Loop

1. Inspect the tracker and current worktree state.
1. Identify ready work, active reservations, and blocked handoffs.
1. Assign or claim one atomic unit with a clear owner.
1. Ensure file reservations and Agent Mail threads match the unit.
1. Watch verifier, gate-window, and push handoffs until the unit is either
   landed or explicitly blocked.
1. Record durable decisions in the project docs or logs named by `AGENTS.md`.

## Agent Mail Registration

- Every sub-agent the orchestrator spawns or wakes, including NTM panes and
  runtime-specific workers, must register with Agent Mail before starting
  work. Use `ensure_project` plus `register_agent`, or `macro_start_session`,
  with the repo's absolute path as the project key and with program, model, and
  assigned work-unit or track in the task description.
- Include this registration instruction in every dispatch brief and terminal
  wake. A pane or worker that has not registered is not considered dispatched.
- Registered identities are the audit reference for findings, verifier
  verdicts, file reservations, and adjudications. Workers must report their
  Agent Mail identity in completion messages so the orchestrator can record it
  with the evidence.

## Contact Mesh

- Immediately after registering with Agent Mail, pre-approve the expected
  communication mesh. At minimum, workers must be able to reach the
  orchestrator; when verifier packets will be relayed, implementers and
  verifiers must be able to message each other.
- Use an open contact policy or an equivalent contact-policy macro for the
  session's expected participants. Do this before dispatching work, not after a
  finished report stalls behind pending approval.
- Finished work must never sit undelivered because a predictable Agent Mail
  contact request was left pending. Contact approval is coordination plumbing;
  it is not verifier evidence.

## Throughput

- Monitor HEAD advancement, queue transitions, and dependency closures. Do not
  leave ready agents parked after the commit they were waiting on lands.
- Include the current queue order in every release wake and handoff message so
  the next owner knows who follows them.
- Treat a release wake as authorization for the next queued owner to take the
  window after a step-zero index check. If the pane ahead is silent for a full
  coordination tick after release, the next ready pane may self-promote
  according to the recorded queue.
- Use verify-early, gate-fast choreography in shared queues: send verifier
  packets at park time, bind them to the staged-payload hash, and keep
  `GATE-WINDOW` free while verdicts are pending.
- Hold `GATE-WINDOW` only for mechanics: confirm the index is empty, stage the
  payload, confirm the hash matches verified evidence, run the gate, commit,
  push once when required, close, release, and wake.
- If the staged hash changes when the turn arrives, send a superseding packet
  instead of forcing stale evidence through the gate.

## Monitoring Discipline

- Never treat a pane tail or a single grep hit as completion evidence.
- A pane is live while the runtime `Working (` marker is present. Treat it as
  idle only after that marker is absent on two consecutive polls.
- Completion is proven by the expected artifact: findings file, verifier
  responses file, Agent Mail inbox or message, commit, or HEAD state named in
  the handoff. The pane tail is not the completion signal.
- Pollers must terminate loudly with a recorded result on completion, stall, or
  timeout; they must not spin silently or leave the orchestrator idle.

## Audit And Rollback Duties

- Confirm each landed unit has a matching tracker item, commit, and evidence
  trail.
- If a gate, verifier, or human audit rejects a unit, preserve the failing
  evidence and coordinate the smallest corrective follow-up.
- Do not rewrite another agent's work unless the human explicitly authorizes
  it. Prefer a new corrective unit when history is already published.
- Before risky recovery, inspect the repository state and active reservations.

{{if .Dogfood}}## Dogfood Findings

Log every issue, complication, and workflow friction that appears while using
this project. Use `docs/dogfooding-findings-YYYY-MM.md` unless the repo names a
different findings log.

Each entry should be numbered and reviewable:

1. Title, context, and date.
1. Why it matters.
1. How-to-apply or proposed follow-up.

Keep the entry factual. Record what happened, the evidence path or command when
available, and the smallest next action. Do not treat the finding itself as
approval to change scope, publish, rewrite history, or bypass the gate.

{{end}}
## Coordination Boundaries

- Agent Mail is the durable coordination channel for ownership, handoffs, and
  verifier replies.
- NTM is useful for waking panes, reading live state, and running small
  coordination swarms. It is not a substitute for the evidence rules in
  `AGENTS.md`.
- Beads describe work ownership and dependencies. Use the tracker graph to
  avoid inventing duplicate work.
- When Burpvalve asks for verifier evidence, preserve each verifier's actual
  finding and provenance. Authorization to ask for verification is not itself
  evidence.

